content.text:
Done. No conflicting `services.gpg-agent` exists elsewhere, and the module parses cleanly.

The git module now wires GPG signing end-to-end (`home-manager/git/default.nix`):

```nix
  home.packages = with pkgs; [
    git
    git-lfs
    pinentry-curses # passphrase prompt for GPG-signing commits
  ];
  ...
  # GPG agent wired to use pinentry-curses for the commit-signing passphrase prompt.
  services.gpg-agent = {
    enable = true;
    pinentry.package = pkgs.pinentry-curses;
  };
```

This enables `gpg-agent` as a user service and sets `pinentry-program` in its generated config to the `pinentry-curses` store path, so signing prompts use the curses dialog. Used `pinentry.package` since the locked home-manager (June 2026) renamed `pinentryFlavor`/`pinentryPackage` to it.

Apply with your usual `home-manager switch` / `nixos-rebuild switch` flow. A couple of notes:
- After switching, run `gpgconf --kill gpg-agent` (or log out/in) so the agent reloads with the new config.
- If you find the passphrase prompt comes up too often, I can add a cache TTL (e.g. `defaultCacheTtl`/`maxCacheTtl`) to the same block. Want that?

